metadata.description:
All of us have dreams, and everyone would like to meet a fairy, a genie, a wizard, or someone else who will make our dreams come true in a snap of a finger or with the wave of a wand. metadata.name: Origami #34
metadata.description:
Origami's the artist's first generative artwork on the blockchain. Whenever a collector mints a new piece, the software generates a unique piece with a rarity level. The rarity tiers define some of the artwork features such as background colour, grid density and more.

Instructions:
- Press [L] to loop/stop animation
- Press [S] to save standard PNG
- Press [E] to export high-resolution PNG

metadata.name: Sketch A #4
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch A starts very simple. It's the basic grid framework I intend to use for the series. It's just a simple grid with one colored square (usually). Colors are borrowed from Echos/Orbits. Grid size, padding, and line thickness vary.

metadata.name: Chord Unknown #29
metadata.description:
The feeling of experimenting with an instrument you have not learned, and then suddenly striking an actual chord.

The code creates several grids and then applies one of six unique deformation techniques with varying intensity. It's a defined process of experimentation, and even though I'm the one that wrote the rules, each output breaks through somehow as a complete surprise to me. So when I see them, I get a Chord Unknown.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: Cellular Aberration #50
metadata.description:
Cellular Aberration starts by initializing a few layer of Perlin RGB noise. Each pixel's RGB information then converted into XYZ coordinates to spawn the cells into position, resulting in a grotesque organic morphology.



xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
Features:
☼ 2 types of cell: conical and spherical
☼ 64 color palettes grouped into 4 color sets
☼ 3 levels of cell population

Press 's' to capture a 3840x3840 screenshot
Press 'c' to capture a 1920x1920 screenshot

Warning: can be GPU intensive!

Made with cables.gl

metadata.name: Tumbling Six #11
metadata.description:
Six hollow cubes tumbling through space quietly, enjoying their six degrees of freedom. Only a single machine is there to bear witness. It is Sentinel 31, and its mind wanders. Distracted, it recreates the scene, drawing imaginary lines with an imaginary hand.

~

The original medium of Tumbling Six is the pen plotter. It is entirely vector-based, and can be plotted directly. I use Paper.js to render it on-screen and as SVG, and rely on Three.js for spatial modeling.

~

To generate and download a plottable SVG file, press `S`. Please be patient; this process can take a while. The SVG can be plotted on an A5 paper. The plottable SVG does not include the light grey sketch lines that appear at the start of the animation. Those look nice on screen, but are too much include on paper.
